         <h1>Mario Puzo, Author Who Made 'The Godfather' a World Addiction, Is Dead at 78 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Mario Puzo , the best-selling novelist and screenwriter who created '' The Godfather '' and made the Corleones the most famous -- and infamous -- of Mafia families and an enduring myth in American culture , died yesterday at his home in Bay Shore , N.Y . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 78 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was heart failure , said his agent , Neil Olson , without elaborating . <br><blue>4</blue>When Mr. Puzo wrote '' The Godfather '' in the late 1960 's , he did it reluctantly . <br><blue>5</blue>His first two novels had received favorable reviews but had earned him a total of $ 6,500 . <br><blue>6</blue>At 45 and in debt , he thought he was going downhill fast as a writer . <br><blue>7</blue>But he had some favorite stories to tell about the Mafia , and for the money , he decided to write a book about Italian-Americans in organized crime . <br><blue>8</blue>From the author 's account , he had scant encouragement from publishers and received an advance of only $ 5,000 . <br><blue>9</blue>But when the book was published in 1969 , it became one of the most phenomenal successes in literary and cinematic history . <br><blue>10</blue>The novel was the No. 1 best seller in the United States and was on the New York Times best-seller list for 67 weeks . <br><blue>11</blue>It was also the most popular novel in England , France , Germany and other countries , and sold more than 21 million copies . <br><blue>12</blue>Then it tripled that success when Francis Coppola filmed it . <br><blue>13</blue>With a screenplay by Mr. Puzo and Mr. Coppola , the film made reputations ( for the director , the writer and many of its stars ) , earned millions of dollars , won Academy Awards for the screenwriters , among others , and became the most quoted movie of its time , with phrases like '' an offer he could n't refuse '' entering the American lexicon . <br><blue>14</blue>The film outdid the book in popularity and in critical respect . <br><blue>15</blue>When it opened in 1972 , Vincent Canby , in his review in The New York Times , called it '' one of the most brutal and moving chronicles of American life ever designed within the limits of popular entertainment . '' <br><blue>16</blue>Led by Marlon Brando as the patriarchal Don Vito Corleone and Al Pacino as the college-educated son Michael who eventually takes control of the family business , the Corleones edged their way into respectability . <br><blue>17</blue>The film was far more than a gangster melodrama ; it was a sweeping portrait of a family that was as devoted to its own sense of values as to violence . <br><blue>18</blue>It was also a commentary on greed in a capitalist society . <br><blue>19</blue>Perhaps the most astonishing aspect of the movie 's success was that it was repeated again and again , as '' The Godfather '' gave rise to '' The Godfather , Part II '' ( 1974 ) and '' The Godfather , Part III '' ( 1990 ) , both also with screenplays by Mr. Puzo and Mr. Coppola . <br><blue>20</blue>Playing various Corleones , Mr. Brando , Mr. Pacino and Robert De Niro gave some of their most memorable screen performances , as did Robert Duvall , James Caan and Diane Keaton in other roles . <br><hr><br><blue>1(9)</blue>: <m_str>The film</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (15_2) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (15_20) 	<m_str>The film</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>It</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>the film</m_str> (13_11) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (17_24) 	<m_str>the movie 's</m_str> (19_7) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (17_11) 	<br><blue>2(6)</blue>: <m_str>its</m_str> (13_51) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (12_10) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (13_25) 	<m_str>The novel</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>It</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (12_2) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (19_13) 	<m_str>the most astonishing aspect of the movie 's success</m_str> (19_2) 	<br><blue>4(15)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (7_18) 	<m_str>the author 's</m_str> (8_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_7) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_40) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_8) 